<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW GNB BATTERY HAS ITS OWN SPARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
People who habitually leave the headlights on and the jumper cables at home are 
target customers for a new battery from GNB Inc. that has a built-in spare. 
</P>
<P>
The Champion Switch combines a conventional 12-volt main battery and a reserve 
into a package that will fit about 70% of the cars on the road, GNB said. 
</P>
<P>
If the main battery dies because the lights were left on, the driver can flip a 
switch on the battery and start the car using the reserve power, which is good 
for 20 engine starts. 
</P>
<P>
The suggested retail price is $109.99, roughly twice the price of conventional 
batteries, although some retailer discounting is likely. 
</P>
<P>
The battery goes on sale in Southeastern states in October and elsewhere in in 
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
