<P>
W.VA. OFFICIAL QUITS TO HALT CRIME PROBE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
West Virginia Atty. Gen. Charlie Brown resigned as part of an agreement to halt 
the second criminal case against him since he took office, a prosecutor said. 
Kanawha County Prosecutor Bill Forbes said he agreed to drop a grand jury 
investigation into Brown's campaign finances and reports that he lied under 
oath during a child custody hearing. Brown, a Democrat, was elected in 1984 and 
reelected without opposition in 1988. In 1986, Brown, 39, was acquitted on 
charges that he shook down his staff for campaign contributions. He contended 
that because he had solicited the contributions after the 1984 election to help 
pay off campaign debts, the actions did not fall under a state law prohibiting 
state officials from soliciting campaign funds from their staffs. 
</P>
