<P>
WITNESS STALLS IMPEACHMENT CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A key witness refused to testify today in the Senate impeachment trial of 
federal Judge Alcee Hastings and was warned that he might be sent to jail for 
contempt of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
William Borders, a former Washington lawyer who was convicted in 1982 of 
conspiracy to bribe Hastings, refused to answer 10 questions about the case 
asked by Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) at a hearing of a special Senate committee 
taking testimony in the trial. 
</P>
<P>
Borders had previously refused to answer questions from the committee on July 
24 and July 27. He was appearing under a subpoena and was granted immunity from 
prosecution for his testimony. 
</P>
<P>
Hastings, a U.S. District Court judge in Florida, was acquitted of the bribery 
charges in a 1983 jury trial but was impeached by the House last year. 
</P>
