</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NICOSIA, Cyprus 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Iran would restore ties with Britain at once if London showed respect for 
Islamic values, Tehran's deputy foreign minister for America and Europe was 
quoted today as saying. 
</P>
<P>
"Relations with Britain can be restored even today," the Iranian news agency 
IRNA reported Mahmoud Vaezi as saying in an interview with the Tehran Times. 
</P>
<P>
Iran broke ties with Britain in March after then supreme leader Ayatollah 
Ruhollah Khomeini called for the killing of British author Salman Rushdie who 
he said had blasphemed against Islam in his novel "The Satanic Verses." 
</P>
<P>
Vaezi's conditions for a renewal of ties appeared to be a softening of the 
Iranian position. It has previously said ties could be reconsidered only when 
Britain ended its support for Rushdie and his novel. 
</P>
