<P>
CONVENTION ROLL CALLER, 72, RESIGNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dorothy Bush, who has called the roll of the states at every Democratic 
National Convention since 1944, resigned today as the party's secretary. 
</P>
<P>
Bush, 72, is familiar to convention watchers as the person who, since the 1944 
convention that nominated Franklin D. Roosevelt, called on the state 
delegations to announce their votes. 
</P>
<P>
When she assumed the secretary's job at age 27, she was the youngest person to 
hold the post and the first female. She is no relation to President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
"What a great experience I have had -- serving with 17 chairmen and heaven 
knows how many wonderful members and friends -- and through the administrations 
of 10 presidents," Bush noted in a resignation letter to DNC Chairman Ron 
Brown. 
</P>
